Incident Response > [T1]: Continuous Incident Response: Before, During, After

When do we do IR?

Figure

The Incident Response starts way before experiencing an attack and can last for a while after the attack. It is a continuous six phases process where each phase informs the next. As a consequence, IR activities are performed before, during, and after a cyber-attack:

  • Before the attack => Preparation: the more you are prepared, the better your IR will be. From our experience, organizations that invest a good deal of time and resources in Preparation are the ones that can handle incidents efficiently. Aside from the tools, processes, and skills, you must prepare the prevention part. Securing your network and improving your defenses will improve the whole IR process. Better prevention means fewer incidents. Otherwise, the IR team will be bombarded with more incidents. 
     
  • During the attack => Detection/Containment/Eradication: The core of the response activities happens during an attack. The detection part starts with an alert from any security control such as a firewall, IPS, or an EDR. One significant thing to highlight here is that detection is not limited to technology solutions, and sometimes incidents get detected by end-users. Some of the APT attacks we investigated started with a report from an end-user for abnormal behavior. Pay attention to your end-users, do not underestimate their reports, and keep in mind that they may not be able to communicate incidents technically. They could be reporting something like "my computer is very slow" or "my PC is acting weirdly."

    Once the attack has been confirmed, it's time to stop further damage. The containment phase's primary goal is to stop the bleeding; like in medical aid, the first thing you will do if you cut yourself is to stop the bleeding by applying direct pressure on the cut or wound with a clean cloth, tissue, or piece of gauze until bleeding stops. Restricting damage will prevent things from worsening and help the IR team react quickly.

    After threat isolation comes the eradication part, where the incident's root cause is removed. Yes, we were able to stop the damage in the containment phase, but there is no guarantee that it will not happen again unless we fix it at the root-cause level. In other words, neutralizing the attack vector and closing the road through which the attack was executed.
     
  • After the attack => Recovery/Lessons Learned: the last two pieces of the IR process; recovery and lessons learned. At some point, you will need to restore the compromised system to the network and put it into production. The recovery phase verifies what have done to eradicate the threat and ensures that the impacted asset is fully operational. Sometimes, the IR teams do not eradicate threats entirely by missing an attack vector. For example, removing a piece of malware from the system, installed through vulnerability exploitation, but leaving the persistent backdoor that the malware installed on the system.

    In the recovery phase, you closely monitor the impacted system after restoring operations to discover other possible threats. Do you see how each IR phase is tied to the phase before and after?

    Finally, it's time to take a step back, look at what happened from start to end and think of what tactical and strategic steps the IR team could have taken to improve the process. What can we do to be better prepared for that type of incident, how can we detect it earlier, what preventive control could have stopped the attack, etc.
Being part of a SOC means you will be involved in IR activities in one way or another, and most probably, this is something you will do daily. Unlike the common belief that IR starts after the attack, it's a non-stop process where each phase builds on top of the other. Incident response is a journey, and each attack is an opportunity for improvement.
